          "body": "Verse 6 is the psalm's theological center of gravity. Without changing a single external circumstance, David moves from 'do not be deaf to me' (v. 1) to 'He has heard' (v. 6). Most commentators note two possible explanations: either a priestly oracle was delivered during the temple worship that assured David of God's answer (comparable to Eli's word to Hannah in 1 Samuel 1:17), or the perfect-tense declaration is David's own faith-leap — his deliberate choice to speak as one already heard, grounded not in an audible word but in God's character. Either reading is consistent with Scripture; both agree that the pivot is not circumstantial. Calvin's commentary on this verse is pointed: 'It is certain that the holy man did not break out into thanksgiving on account of any change which had taken place in his outward condition; but his mind being tranquilized by prayer, he rested in the confidence that God would be his helper.' The pivot from lament to praise within a single psalm session is not emotional volatility; it is the fruit of theology — God's character as faithful hearer becomes more real to David than his unresolved circumstances."
