          "body": "Verse 7 produces three consequence-clauses from a single act of trust. Because David's heart trusts in God: (1) he is helped, (2) his heart exults, and (3) with his song he thanks Him. The vocabulary is military but the application is comprehensive. 'Strength' (oz) is the power to engage — God does not merely keep David from harm but empowers him to act. 'Shield' (magen) is the defensive complement — God absorbs what would otherwise strike David dead. Together they form a picture of total provision: no gap between offense and defense, no moment when David is exposed. The exultation (alaz, v. 7) that follows is not relief; it is triumph — the word carries the connotation of the victor's shout. And the 'song' (shir) with which David thanks God completes the circle back to the lifted hands of verse 2: the same body that oriented toward the sanctuary in petition now lifts its voice in thanksgiving. Prayer and praise are the bookends of the psalm's structural movement, and both are directed toward the same God."
