          "body": "The final two verses perform one of the most characteristic moves in Davidic theology: the personal is inseparable from the communal. Verse 8 generalizes the strength of verse 7 — what Yahweh is to David personally (strength, saving defense), He is to 'His people' and 'His anointed.' Verse 9 closes with four imperatives addressed to God on behalf of Israel: save, bless, shepherd, carry. The shepherd metaphor (ra'ah, v. 9) is one of Scripture's oldest and most loaded images for God's governance of His people (Psalm 23; Isaiah 40:11; Ezekiel 34:11-16), and it reaches its canonical fulfillment in Jesus, who identifies Himself as the Good Shepherd who lays down His life for the sheep (John 10:11). The Messianic freight of verse 8's 'anointed' (mashiach) means that the psalm's final movement is not merely a prayer for David's Israel but a typological anticipation: the one who will be God's saving defense for His anointed, who will shepherd and carry the people forever, is the Son of David whose rule has no end (Luke 1:33). The psalm that began with one man crying from the edge of the pit ends with a whole people carried by their Shepherd into the forever (olam) that death cannot interrupt."
