      {
        "number": 3,
        "title": "The pivot — blessed be the Lord, because He has heard",
        "range": "28:6-7",
        "excerpt": "Blessed be the Lord, because He has heard the voice of my supplication. The Lord is my strength and my shield; my heart trusts in Him, and I am helped.",
        "body": "Verse 6 is the most structurally significant verse in the psalm, and it requires careful handling. David has been in petition mode through verse 5 — imperative verbs, conditional clauses, future fears. Then without narrative transition, without any reported divine speech, without a change of scene, the grammar shifts entirely to declarative praise: 'Blessed be the Lord, because He has heard.' The Hebrew perfect tense ('has heard') marks a completed action. The praise is not hopeful anticipation but confident declaration.\n\nTwo explanations are offered by commentators. The first, favored by Peter Craigie (*Psalms 1-50*, WBC, 1983) and many Psalms scholars, is that a priestly oracle was delivered in the sanctuary during the worship liturgy — a divine word through an authorized mediator that assured David his prayer was received (comparable to Eli's reassurance of Hannah in 1 Samuel 1:17 or the prophetic answer to Jehoshaphat in 2 Chronicles 20:14-17). The second, favored by John Calvin and Spurgeon, is that the pivot reflects the psalmist's own faith-movement — the prayer itself, offered in trust, produces a settled confidence in God's hearing that precedes any visible answer. Both readings are theologically sound and historically attested in Israel's worship. Either way, the structural lesson is the same: biblical praise does not require prior visible resolution. The pivot from lament to praise is an act of faith, not a report of changed circumstances.\n\nVerse 7 then unpacks what it means to have been helped. 'The Lord is my strength and my shield' — oz (offensive power) and magen (defensive protection) — together cover the full compass of military need. David does not merely find that God has removed the threat; he finds that God has replaced his emptiness with His own strength. The trust (batach) that produces this experience is not passive waiting but active reliance — placing one's full weight on God's character as if He were the solid ground beneath an unstable surface. The consequence flows logically: 'therefore my heart exults.' The word alaz carries a note of triumph, the victor's shout rather than the survivor's relief. And the song (shir) of thanksgiving completes the psalm's symmetry: the hands lifted toward the sanctuary in verse 2 give way to the voice lifted in song in verse 7. The physical body that prayed is the same physical body that sings.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Barakh* (blessed) — the Piel stem used here is the form of blessing-declaration, not merely a wish. *Tachanun* (supplication) — plural of the root for seeking grace (chanan); echoes the divine self-description 'gracious' (chanun) in Exodus 34:6. *Batach* (trust) — to lean on, to be confident in; never a passive state in the Psalms but always an active orientation of the will. *Alaz* (exults) — to rejoice with triumph; used of Israel's joy after the Red Sea crossing in Exodus 15:1 (English translation varies)."
      },
      {
        "number": 4,
        "title": "From 'my rock' to 'their shepherd' — the Davidic king and the people of God",
        "range": "28:8-9",
        "excerpt": "The Lord is their strength, and He is a saving defense to His anointed. Save Your people and bless Your inheritance; be their shepherd also, and carry them forever.",
        "body": "The final two verses perform the characteristic Davidic move from personal deliverance to communal intercession. The transition is not a literary afterthought; it reflects a theology of kingship at the core of Israel's covenant structure. The Davidic king is not a private individual who happens to rule; he is the mediatorial figure through whom God's purposes for the whole people are administered. What Yahweh is to David — strength, saving defense — He is also to 'His people' and 'His anointed' (v. 8). The anointed (mashiach) in verse 8 is best read as David's self-reference in his royal capacity, though the canonical freight of the term means that no interpreter can stop there.\n\nVerse 9 issues four imperatives on behalf of Israel: save, bless, shepherd, carry. The progression is not random. 'Save' (yasha) addresses the immediate crisis — rescue from the current danger. 'Bless' (barakh) addresses the ongoing provision — God's active favor and increase upon the people. 'Shepherd' (ra'ah) addresses the mode of governance — not military domination but the tender attentiveness of a flock-keeper who knows each sheep by name. 'Carry' (nasa) addresses the permanent commitment — to bear up, to lift and transport those who cannot move under their own strength. The word nasa is the same word used of the angel who 'carried' Elijah (1 Kings 19:5 LXX equivalent) and of God who 'carried' Israel through the wilderness (Deuteronomy 1:31; Isaiah 46:3-4). The 'forever' (olam) that closes the psalm stretches the carrying beyond any single crisis, beyond David's own lifetime, into the eschatological horizon where God's people are permanently upheld.\n\nThe Messianic reading of this psalm's closing is not eisegesis but canonical obligation. The 'anointed' of verse 8 who is God's saving defense, the 'shepherd' of verse 9 who carries the people forever — these titles converge in the New Testament's identification of Jesus as the Son of David, the Good Shepherd (John 10:11), and the one who 'is able to keep you from stumbling and to present you before His glory blameless with great joy' (Jude 1:24). What David asks God to do for Israel in verse 9, Jesus enacts for the new covenant people permanently: He is the mashiach who is simultaneously the shepherd and the one being carried through death and resurrection by the Father, so that those in Him are carried as well.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Mashiach* (anointed) — the term that will give its Greek equivalent *Christos* its full theological weight in the New Testament. *Ra'ah* (shepherd) — the pastoral verb used of God's governance of Israel throughout the Prophets and Psalms (Psalm 23:1; Isaiah 40:11; Ezekiel 34). *Nasa* (carry) — to lift, bear, carry; used of God bearing His people's iniquities (Isaiah 53:4, 11) and of God physically sustaining Israel through the wilderness (Deuteronomy 1:31). *Olam* (forever) — the age, the long duration, the eschatological stretch beyond current crisis."
      }
